{% block bodyContent %}

  <p>Content designers should be familiar with the social model of disability. Find out more about <a href="https://www.scope.org.uk/about-us/social-model-of-disability/">the social model on Scope's website</a>.</p>
  <p>We do say things like:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>people living with a disability, or disabled person</li>
    <li>people with diabetes</li>
    <li>wheelchair user</li>
  </ul>
  <p>We do not say:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>afflicted by</li>
    <li>suffering from</li>
    <li>victim of</li>
    <li>confined to a wheelchair</li>
    <li>handicapped</li>
    <li>diabetic person</li>
    <li>mentally ill</li>
    <li>sick or diseased person</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 id="mental-health">Mental health</h2>
  <p>We do not describe people as mentally ill.</p>
  <p>We do say:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>mental health condition</li>
    <li>mental health problems</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Accessibility</h2>
  <p>NHS digital services should be accessible to everyone who needs them. Follow <a href="/accessibility/content">our guidance on accessibility for content designers, writers and editors</a> in the digital service manual.</p>


